CHAPTER XXXVII.

1. Aliena] “Estranged,hostile.”

2. Id. adeo] The force of adeo is here emphatic, “in fact: '’ being a stronger affirmation of a previous proposition. So again, id adeo malum, at the end of this chapter. Comp. Juyur. (36. eum imperium Numidiae sine mora habiturum z id adeo mature posse evenire ς and again 110, 111.

3. Aluntur, etc] “They get their living without anxiety in tumults and seditionS, because poverty wants little, and has nothing to lose.” liabetur, i.q. toleratur.

4. Ea. vero] A demonstration, introduced for emphasis, changes the construction. Comp. for the force of the pronoun,- Catil. 53. in fuga salutem sperare ea vero dementia est. Cic. Nat. Deor. ii. 10. reliqua. pars mundi ea et ipsa tota natura fervida est. Sec note 10 on Catil. 12.

5. Praeceps ierat] “Had become utterly demoralized, or reekless.” Comp. Catil. 25. luxuria atque inopia praeceps abierat. Persius, iii. 41. imus, imus praecipites.
